commText: Prithvi Shaw and Warner are at the crease. Prithvi Shaw is on strike. Arshad Khan will open the attack
Arshad Khan to Prithvi Shaw, 1 run, short of length around the ribs, Shaw is rushed on the pull and gloves it to short fine
Stat: LSG have won each of the 13 IPL matches in which they have scored 160 or more batting first.
The physio is running out as Shaw was struck on his hand. Struck on the left hand. All fine and we resume..
Arshad Khan to Warner, no run, I0$ good length ball swings away, Warner has a loose waft and is beaten on the outside edge

Arshad Khan to Warner, no run, uhhh! Now he's beaten the other edge. Shortens the length and gets the ball to nip in, Warner is looking to defend on the back foot and is cut into half, the ball flies past the inside edge
Arshad Khan to Warner, 1 run, on a length and outside off, Warner mistimes the drive wide of mid-off
Arshad Khan to Prithvi Shaw, 1 run, back of a length and cramping Shaw up, tucked square on the leg-side
Arshad Khan to Warner, FOUR, Warner manufactures a boundary. Fraction short and outside off, Warner fetches the shot and whip-pulls it through the vacant mid-wicket region
Naveen-ul-Haq, right-arm fast medium, comes into the attack
Naveen-ul-Haq to Prithvi Shaw, no run, in-angler around off, Shaw offers a straight bat and pushes it to mid-off
Naveen-ul-Haq to Prithvi Shaw, FOUR, width on offer and Shaw does not miss out, he reaches with an open face and slices it over point. There was a sweeper but he had no chance of stopping that
Wide slip in place

Naveen-ul-Haq to Prithvi Shaw, FOUR, glorious! Good length ball outside off, Shaw drives through the line and that too on the rise, struck it uppishly but into the vacant extra cover region. Rahul shakes his head behind the stumps
Naveen-ul-Haq to Prithvi Shaw, no run, fuller and closer to off, Shaw pushes it back to Naveen-ul-Haq
Naveen-ul-Haq to Prithvi Shaw, 1 run, missed out there. Full and outside off again, Shaw goes hard and drags it off the inner half to mid-on
Round the wicket to Warner
Naveen-ul-Haq to Warner, no run, good length ball around off, Warner shuffes across and sits down, misses the lap and is struck on the body
Arshad Khan to Prithvi Shaw, 1 run, fullish delivery and Shaw pats it into the off-side, Warner quickly crosses over
Arshad Khan to Warner, 1 run, short and into the body, Warner pulls to deep square leg
Arshad Khan to Prithvi Shaw, no run, I0$ good length ball angled across, Shaw stays rooted to the crease and has a tentative poke, the angle keeps taking the ball away and beats the outside edge
Arshad Khan to Prithvi Shaw, no run, I0$ back of a length on off, Shaw looks to turn it into the leg-side and ekes out an inside edge onto the pad
Arshad Khan to Prithvi Shaw, FOUR, not off the middle but enough to pick up a boundary. I0$ short of length delivery, Shaw slaps it straight down the ground and it came off the sticker

Best batting recoveries after losing 7 wickets for < 100 (IPL) 95 - 59/7 to 154/9 - SRH vs GT, Ahmedabad, 2023 78 - 75/7 to 153/8 - RR vs MI, Ahmedabad, 2014 73 - 94/7 to 167/7 - LSG vs DC, Lucknow, 2024 55 - 92/7 to 147/8 - RCB vs CSK, Chennai, 2011 Final 53 - 68/7 to 121/7 - MI vs RPS, Mumbai WS, 2016 - LSG’s 167/7 is the highest innings total for a team after losing their first seven wickets for under 100 in IPL history, bettering SRH’s 154/9 vs GT in Ahmedabad last year.
Arshad Khan to Prithvi Shaw, no run, I0$ short of length around off, Shaw angles it to backward point
Now Warner is getting some treatment by the physio. He was struck on the hand while attempting the lap off Naveen. The left hand is being strapped. All sorted now and we go again..
Yash Thakur, right-arm medium, comes into the attack
Yash Thakur to Warner, no run, I0$ angled outside off, Warner mistimes the cut and immediately feels the shock on his injured hand
Yash Thakur to Warner, 2 runs, uses the angle going across him and guides it behind square on the off-side, easy two
Yash Thakur to Warner, THATS OUT!! Bowled!!

Yash Thakur to Warner, out Bowled!! Played on! Yash Thakur starts off from where left off the other night. He was a bit lucky here but he won't be complaining. Warner shuffles across once again to play the pick up shot or the lap, gets cramped for room and is struck on the back thigh, the ball lobs up and spins back onto the stumps, dislodging the leg-bail. Warner tries to push the ball away but is a bit late. Warner b Yash Thakur 8(9) [4s-1]
Jake Fraser-McGurk, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Yash Thakur to Fraser-McGurk, no run, I0$ full and outside off, Fraser-McGurk stays rooted to the crease and drags it to mid-on

Yash Thakur to Fraser-McGurk, SIX, Fraser-McGurk off the mark in IPL with a six. He's fearless and does not back away from playing his shots. Short of length delivery and he loves it there, hangs back and hammers the pull over deep mid-wicket
Yash Thakur to Fraser-McGurk, no run, good length ball around off, Fraser-McGurk pushes it on the up to mid-off

Arshad Khan to Prithvi Shaw, FOUR, crunched! Fuller than a good length and Shaw drives through the line, not much feet movement but the hands flow through the shot, struck it straight down the ground and gets a thumbs up from Fraser-McGurk

Arshad Khan to Prithvi Shaw, 1 run, direct hit and Shaw was not in the frame. He turns it to the right of the bowler and sets off, Arshad runs across and collects the ball, turns around and throw at the bowler's end, misses and Shaw survives
Arshad Khan to Fraser-McGurk, no run, short and banged into the wicket, Fraser-McGurk swings hard on the pull and the ball flies over the top-edge

Arshad Khan to Fraser-McGurk, SIX, the first one just cleared the rope and this one sailed into the stands. LSG bowlers need to quickly learn, Fraser-McGurk loves anything slightly short, he clears his front leg and has a free swing, connects cleanly and the ball whistles over wide long-on
Arshad Khan to Fraser-McGurk, no run, that's better. Good length and no room on offer, Fraser-McGurk knocks it back to Arshad
Jake Fraser-McGurk in BBL 2023/24 Inns: 8 Runs: 257 Avg: 32.12 SR: 158.64 50s: 2 HS: 70 4s/6s: 17/18

Arshad Khan to Fraser-McGurk, FOUR, tries to angle it outside off and ends up offering width, Fraser-McGurk throws his bat on the drive and slices it over the backward point region. No one in the deep to stop that

1-5 Over Summary: >> Shaw strikes back-to-back boundaries off Naveen >> Warner cops a blow on his wrists >> Warner chops one back onto his stumps, Thakur strikes >> Fraser-McGurk hits a second ball six on IPL debut >> The Aussie scores another six next over. DC 45/1 after five.
Krunal Pandya, Left arm orthodox, comes into the attack
Krunal Pandya to Prithvi Shaw, 1 run, flatter and at the stumps, Shaw works it to square leg and hands the strike back to Fraser-McGurk

Krunal Pandya to Fraser-McGurk, 5 wides, this is all Fraser-McGurk. He's put the pressure on the LSG bowlers. Krunal darts it down leg and Rahul cannot do much, he gets a hand but the ball still runs away to the fence

Krunal Pandya to Fraser-McGurk, leg byes, 1 run, sliding in with the angle, Fraser-McGurk swings across the line and misses, struck down leg and the ball rolls into the off-side, Shaw quickly crosses over
Krunal Pandya to Prithvi Shaw, FOUR, this is smart batting. Shaw knows Krunal is darting them in, he moves inside the line and helps it over backward square leg, one bounce and over the ropes
Krunal Pandya to Prithvi Shaw, FOUR, the length is shortened and Shaw is quick to pounce, he pulls it over mid-on and manages to clear the infield easily
Krunal Pandya to Prithvi Shaw, no run, short of length and angled in, Shaw misses the tuck and is struck on the thigh pad
Run-out check sent upstairs. Shaw was struggling but might have just made it. Yes, he's in comfortably. Not Out

Krunal Pandya to Prithvi Shaw, 2 runs, makes room and Krunal follows him, nudged into the leg-side field and the pair decide to go for the second, Shaw is not as nimble as Fraser-McGurk and was struggling at a point, but makes it thanks to a wide throw

Timeout! This is a good start for Delhi Capitals. Warner struggled to get going but Shaw has got them off to a flying start again and is joined by an adventurous Fraser-McGurk. Lucknow need to put the squeeze in the middle overs now to get back into the game.
Stat: This is DC’s joint highest Powerplay score this season, alongside 62/0 against CSK in Visakhapatnam. They have crossed 50 in this phase in five matches out of six.
Ravi Bishnoi, right-arm leg break, comes into the attack
Ravi Bishnoi to Fraser-McGurk, no run, starts off with a fast googly, Fraser-McGurk didn't read it well and got an inside edge onto the back pad. Risky with him playing with that bat pad gap
Ravi Bishnoi to Fraser-McGurk, no run, another googly, bowled very short. Fraser-McGurk rocks back for a big pull but ball escapes under his bat
Ravi Bishnoi to Fraser-McGurk, 1 run, skids one through onto off stump, the batter slightly late on the punch to the left of covers
Ravi Bishnoi to Prithvi Shaw, no run, pitched fuller and quicker onto off, pushed back to Bishnoi
Ravi Bishnoi to Prithvi Shaw, no run, 100.7 clicks, a fast googly onto the pads. Shaw went for a slog sweep but couldn't connect
Ravi Bishnoi to Prithvi Shaw, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Ravi Bishnoi to Prithvi Shaw, out Caught by Pooran!! One run and a wicket! What an over from Ravi Bishnoi who has his arms aloft with raised pointer fingers in celebration, revelling in the moment!! Fired in onto the pads, Shaw takes it on with a slog sweep but errs in timing. Pooran hares forward from deep mid-wicket and dives forwards to complete the catch as the ball was dying on him. Crucial breakthrough for the hosts! Prithvi Shaw c Pooran b Ravi Bishnoi 32(22) [4s-6]
Rishabh Pant, left handed bat, comes to the crease
Naveen-ul-Haq [1.0-0-9-0] is back into the attack
Naveen-ul-Haq to Fraser-McGurk, 1 run, pace off, length ball outside off. Fraser-McGurk pulls it across the line towards deep square
Naveen-ul-Haq to Pant, 2 runs, back of length angling across on fourth stump, sits up nicely for Pant to punch square of the wicket for a couple of runs to get off the mark
Naveen-ul-Haq to Pant, no run, fuller length delivery onto the stumps, defended back towards Naveen
Naveen-ul-Haq to Pant, 1 run, pace off and angling to off stump, Pant with a watchful push towards point for a single
Naveen-ul-Haq to Fraser-McGurk, 1 run, pace off, back of length. Fraser-McGurk was early and tamely guides his pull towards deep square
Naveen-ul-Haq to Pant, 1 run, length ball onto the thigh pad, clipped towards backward square
Ravi Bishnoi to Pant, 2 runs, full onto off stump, driven to the right of the cover fielder. A bit of hesitation over the second but both batters make it safe
Ravi Bishnoi to Pant, no run, googly that finishes outside off. Pant tries to cut it away but can't connect
Ravi Bishnoi to Pant, no run, another googly, ends very wide. Cut towards cover point who makes a lunging stop and negates the single
Ravi Bishnoi to Pant, 1 run, leg spinner, a bit closer to the stumps. Driven down to long-off
Ravi Bishnoi to Fraser-McGurk, 1 run, flat delivery on off, Fraser-McGurk underedges his big slog onto the ground towards long-on
Ravi Bishnoi to Pant, no run, finishes with another googly, Pant anticipated it but couldn't do anything. Tries a reverse sweep but can make no contact
Yash Thakur [1.0-0-8-1] is back into the attack
Yash Thakur to Fraser-McGurk, no run, pace off, full and wide. Driven straight towards extra cover
Yash Thakur to Fraser-McGurk, no run, nails the yorker, lands it perfectly between the two boots of Fraser-McGurk. The batter can't do anything about that
Yash Thakur to Fraser-McGurk, no run, slower delivery outside off, a big swing and a miss for the Australian
Yash Thakur to Fraser-McGurk, 1 run, low full toss, pushed down to long-on
Yash Thakur to Pant, 1 run, length ball that skids onto the thigh pad, turned to mid-wicket
Yash Thakur to Fraser-McGurk, no run, full outside off, Fraser-McGurk throws the kitchen sink at it but the ball trickles past his bat. That's just 13 runs off the last 4 overs, no boundaries
6-10 Over Summary: >> Krunal comes on and is taken for 16 runs >> Bishnoi strikes in his first over, Shaw falls for 32 >> Just 13 runs have come after the powerplay

Ravi Bishnoi to Pant, 1 run, googly from a short of length, Pant was a bit uneasy and awkwardly chips it over Bishnoi for a single. Shouts of 'catch' for a moment but Bishnoi had to be 10 feet tall to take that
Ravi Bishnoi to Fraser-McGurk, 2 runs, flat delivery outside off, slapped to the left of long-off for a couple of runs
Ravi Bishnoi to Fraser-McGurk, 1 run, quick and full at the stumps, slammed down to long-on

Ravi Bishnoi to Pant, SIX, there comes the Rishabh Pant countercharge!! A boundary after 29 deliveries.. Dances down to the pitch of it and hoists it over the bowler's head for a straight six as Bishnoi floats it up slightly.

Ravi Bishnoi to Pant, FOUR, dances down again and Bishnoi shortens the length and tries to squeeze it wide outside off. Pant adjusts, reaches out and slaps it to the right of long-off for a boundary. Skipper Rahul continues to encourage his bowler
Ravi Bishnoi to Pant, 1 run, flat delivery outside off, cut square of the wicket for a single. 15 runs off the over
Marcus Stoinis, right-arm medium, comes into the attack
Stoinis to Pant, 1 run, pace off and full, Pant goes for a big heave but inside halves towards deep mid-wicket

Stoinis to Fraser-McGurk, no run, dropped!! Bishnoi the fielder. A pace off, length ball outside off. Fraser-McGurk slams it hard but straight towards extra cover. Pops in and out the hands of the fielder who pulled off a stunner last game to dismiss Williamson
Stoinis to Fraser-McGurk, 1 run, pace off and short, Fraser-McGurk horribly early on the pull and hits it tamely to square leg

Stoinis to Pant, FOUR, that's the shot that would sometimes be giving nightmares to Jimmy Anderson!! Rishabh Pant brings out the reverse ramp and gets enough of a connection to hit this pace off, full delivery over short third. Couple of bounce and four!!
Stoinis to Pant, no run, a slower bouncer from Stoinis, Pant tries an upper cut but can't connect

Stoinis to Pant, FOUR, hard length delivery near the thighs, Pant shuffles inwards and ramps it over short fine. A captain's knock so far by RP, he knew he had to take the responsibility against their part-timer with Fraser-McGurk struggling, and ekes out two bounbdaries off it
Krunal Pandya [1.0-0-16-0] is back into the attack
Krunal Pandya to Fraser-McGurk, wide, too far wide outside off

Youngest to 3,000 IPL runs 24y, 215d - Shubman Gill 26y, 186d - Virat Kohli 26y, 191d - Rishabh Pant 26y, 320d - Sanju Samson 27y, 161d - Suresh Raina Of the 25 batters to have aggregated 3,000-plus runs in the IPL till date, Pant’s strike-rate of 148.4 is bettered only by AB de Villiers (151.68) and Chris Gayle (148.96)

Krunal Pandya to Fraser-McGurk, SIX, launched!! Right out of the meat of the bat as Krunal dishes out an arm ball in the swinging arc of Jake Fraser-McGurk. Clears his front leg and heaves it over deep mid-wicket
Krunal Pandya to Fraser-McGurk, SIX, six more!! This one is fired quick outside off, Fraser-McGurk gets closer, gets under it and slams it over deep extra cover for a maximum

Krunal Pandya to Fraser-McGurk, SIX, a hat-trick of sixes!! And that's why this young lad is making so much buzz on social media. A flat delivery onto off, Fraser-McGurk is fearless as he makes some room and gives it a big, old golf swing over long-off. Making an International bowler like Krunal Pandya look pedestrain out here!
Krunal Pandya to Fraser-McGurk, wide, jeez, a 116 click bouncer from Pandya, Fraser-McGurk ducks under it and Rahul does very well to collect that like a hockey goalkeeper over his shoulders
Krunal Pandya to Fraser-McGurk, no run, full outside off, a swing and a miss
Krunal Pandya to Fraser-McGurk, no run, flat delivery outside off, Fraser-McGurk is beaten
Krunal Pandya to Fraser-McGurk, 1 run, flat delivery at the stumps, slapped down to long-on
Yash Thakur [2.0-0-10-1] is back into the attack
Yash Thakur to Fraser-McGurk, FOUR, slot ball outside off, Fraser-McGurk throws his bat out at it. Gives it a big swing and toe-ends it over backward point for a boundary

Yash Thakur to Fraser-McGurk, 3 runs, on a length angling onto the thigh pad, clipped softly behind square and that's good enough for a triple. That's a fifty on IPL debut for Jake Fraser-McGurk, hopefully just the start of many more beautiful things for this incredibly talented hiiter from South Australia!
Yash Thakur to Pant, 1 run, length ball outside off, cut towards deep point
Yash Thakur to Fraser-McGurk, 1 run, goes very full outside off, Fraser-McGurk shuffles in and slams it down towards long-off

Yash Thakur to Pant, SIX, pace off and back of length on off, Pant reads it off the hands and gives it powerful pull over deep mid-wicket for a maximum. It felt like he literally snatched that out the hands off Thakur and hit it away into the stands...
Yash Thakur to Pant, no run, full delivery on the pads, Pant tries to clip it away but misses. Deflects off the legs towards the keeper
Naveen-ul-Haq [2.0-0-15-0] is back into the attack
Naveen-ul-Haq to Fraser-McGurk, 1 run, wide yorker, Fraser-McGurk shuffles inwards to get under the ball and slam it down to long-off
Naveen-ul-Haq to Pant, 1 run, back of length near the ribs, pulled behind square for a single

Naveen-ul-Haq to Fraser-McGurk, 2 runs, pace off and on a length outside off, Fraser-McGurk tries to slap it over deep extra but the bat turns on impact. Lands safely between extra cover and the fielder at sweeper
Naveen-ul-Haq to Fraser-McGurk, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Naveen-ul-Haq to Fraser-McGurk, out Caught by Arshad Khan!! Muted celebrations from the home team. Naveen-ul-Haq goes full and almost on the wide line outside off. Fraser-McGurk goes chasing for a big heave through the line but slices it down towards the deep backward point fielder. Nicely judged by Arshad Khan. End of a truly special debut knock by a kid who was making all the right noise heading into this IPL season! Fraser-McGurk c Arshad Khan b Naveen-ul-Haq 55(35) [4s-2 6s-5]
Tristan Stubbs, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Naveen-ul-Haq to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, length ball outside off, guided down to third-man

Naveen-ul-Haq to Pant, FOUR, bouncer onto the body, Pant shuffles in for a swivel pull and top edges it over the keeper's head for a very fine boundary to the leg side. DC are in a hurry to end this now...

11-15 Over Summary: >> Pant breaks the shackles, first boundary after 29 balls (10.4) >> Fraser-McGruk is dropped at cover on 24 >> Stoinis comes on and is taken for 10 runs >> Fraser-McGruk smashes Krunal for hattrick of sixes >> Fifty on debut for Fraser-McGruk, just 31 balls >> Yash Thakur is hammered for 15 runs, DC running away >> Naveen ends Fraser-McGruk's entertaining knock
Ravi Bishnoi [3.0-0-20-1] is back into the attack
Ravi Bishnoi to Tristan Stubbs, no run, flighted up leg spinner just outside off, pushed back to Bishnoi
Ravi Bishnoi to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, flat delivery outside off, cut towards deep backward point
Ravi Bishnoi to Pant, THATS OUT!! Stumped!!

Ravi Bishnoi to Pant, out Stumped!! A twist in the tale? Pant dances down the track for a big slog. Bishnoi with a brave hearted full delivery that spins away from the batter. Pant loses his shape and his bat, and the bat falls onto the arms of KL Rahul, who was undistrubed as he had his eyes on the stumping. Second wicket for Bishnoi. Pant st Rahul b Ravi Bishnoi 41(24) [4s-4 6s-2]

Time-out. DC are in the driver's seat despite these two wickets. The equation is down to less than a run a ball, just some sensible cricket and they should get over the line. Lucknow need a real miracle to save their record of defending scores.
Shai Hope, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Ravi Bishnoi to Shai Hope, FOUR, flighted up and wide, Hope gets closer with a big stride and drives it powerfully in front of square. All timing on that one to start off with a boundary!
Ravi Bishnoi to Shai Hope, no run, pitched up and was the googly, Hope with another big stride watchfully defends
Ravi Bishnoi to Shai Hope, no run, googly, skids through from outside off. Hope defends from his crease
Krunal Pandya [2.0-0-37-0] is back into the attack
Krunal Pandya to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, tossed up delivery, Stubbs dances out and drives it down to long-off
Krunal Pandya to Shai Hope, 2 runs, arm ball from a length, Hope shuffles in and clips it cutely towards fine leg
Krunal Pandya to Shai Hope, 1 run, another arm ball, gets a bit of extra bounce. Punched to the right of Pandya for a single
Krunal Pandya to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, flat delivery on off, punched to sweeper cover off the backfoot
Krunal Pandya to Shai Hope, 1 run, spinning away from middle and off, Hope gets a big stride closer and pushes it down to long-off

Krunal Pandya to Tristan Stubbs, 2 runs, arm ball that ends down leg, Stubbs premeditated to play the reverse sweep and gets it behind square between the two fielders in the circle. Won't go for four as sweeper cover cuts it off
Yash Thakur [3.0-0-25-1] is back into the attack
Yash Thakur to Shai Hope, no run, pitched up delivery on off, driven to short cover
Yash Thakur to Shai Hope, 2 runs, slower delivery, on a length outside off. Hope with a watchful punch to the right of sweeper cover for a couple of runs
Yash Thakur to Shai Hope, 1 run, full delivery onto off, Hope pushes it towards mid-off for a single. Direct hit from the fielder but the batter is home and dry
Yash Thakur to Tristan Stubbs, 2 runs, hard length onto off stump, pulled behind square. Stubbs takes on the arm of the thrower in the deep and picks up the second run
One hit away now...
Yash Thakur to Tristan Stubbs, 1 run, full and straight, neatly driven to long-on
Yash Thakur to Shai Hope, no run, pace off and on a length on off, tucked to mid-wicket
Arshad Khan [3.0-0-28-0] is back into the attack

Arshad Khan to Tristan Stubbs, SIX, into the crowds and I0$ A length ball onto middle and leg, Stubbs with a nonchalant pull over deep backward square leg for a maximum. DC back to winning ways, win by 6 wickets with 11 balls to spare!

23:12 Local Time, 17:42 GMT, 23:12 IST: LSGs home domination is curbed. Their streak of defending totals comes to an end. The hunters have been hunted, and they have been stung by the new, potent venom from South Australia sprinkled with a bit of fearless bite from the leader of the team that features three tigers on their emblem. Chasing 167, Delhi didnt get the best of starts as Warner copped a blow to his wrists and then chopped one back onto his stumps. However, that brought the youngster Jake Fraser-McGurk to the crease and he got off the mark with two sixes in the IPL. Fraser-McGurk was well supported by Prithvi Shaw who scored six fours in the powerplay, but holed out trying to attack Ravi Bishnoi. There came a lull post the powerplay as LSG slipped in four quiet overs, with Bishnoi leading the charge. Fraser-McGurk was struggling for timing, and the skipper Rishabh Pant took the mantle on himself. He attacked Bishnoi for a four and six, and that titled the complextion of the game.

Couple overs later, Fraser-McGurk hit a hat-trick of sixes against Krunal Pandya, and the next over from Yash Thakur also went for plenty of runs. The 22-year-old notched up a fifty on IPL debut, but couldn't stay till the end as he sliced one to deep point off Naveen-ul-Haq. Rishabh Pant played a real captain's knock to take the pressure off the debutant, but he too couldn't stay till the end as he was stumped dancing down the track against Bishnoi. However, I0$and they managed to get through the line with almost two overs to spare. Rishabh Pant and co. are back to winning ways, the LSG juggernaut have been stopped. Stick around for the presenations...

KL Rahul: If I want to be harsh, I think we were 15-20 runs short, we got off to a good start, we could have capitalised and got 180. There was a bit of help for the seamers, the odd ball kept low. Kuldeep made its use (and got those wickets.) The new guys when they come in, it's pretty unknown for us. He (Jake Fraser-McGurk) hit the ball well, credit to him. We always walk in with the same mindset, want to hit the right areas. We got Warner in the powerplay, got a couple of wickets after the powerplay. The set batters - Pant and McGurk took the game away from us after that dropped catch. We travel tomorrow and play an afternoon game (on Sunday). That's how the schedule goes, need to turn up, could be tough during Indian summers. In hindsight you can always wonder you could have done something different. There wasn't much spin after Axar's over, so I thought Pooran could have put some pressure on the opposition, if he was set. He would have been dangerous, but credit to Kuldeep for getting him out. He (Mayank Yadav) is feeling good, he looks good, but we don't want to rush him. We need to protect his body, he's itching to go. Need to make sure that he's hundred percent (fit) before he comes back.

Jake Fraser-McGurk: I spent the last 5-6 games on the sidelines and was itching to have a go. It was more of trying not to swing too hard, trying to find the middle of the bat and that's what I have been trying to do in the last 12 months. I loved the one over cover, nothing better than hitting over the off-side. It is something that I continue to learn and do, batting outside of the powerplay and I will get better by playing more games. I am so happy to be out there, this is a different world out here, heard about it but to experience it.. it is an amazing time to come to India.

Stats by Roshan

Rishabh Pant: Little relief, we wanted a win badly. I was talking to the boys saying we need to think like champions, we need to keep fighting hard. (On bowling) We have phases where we are not up to the mark, some individuals have to take responsibility for that. However, we stick together as a group. Some things you can control, some things we can't. (On team combination) I think we are getting closer to the right XI, but we've had so many injuries in this group. However, you can't keep complaining about that. (On Fraser-McGurk) Hopefully, we've found our new number 3, haven't thought too much about it. Hope he can continue.

Kuldeep Yadav | Player of the Match: Was tough when I wasn't fit. Got injured first game and was difficult to see the team struggling in the middle overs. Credit goes to Patrick (Farhart) to maintain my fitness and get me ready quickly. All three were important wickets, it was crucial to get wickets in the middle overs to control the run rate. I liked the first and second wicket, I have played a lot against Pooran and the execution for that was right. I was clear with my plans, just the length matters for me as a spinner. Very clear and confident with my skills. Whenever I feel the DRS call is 50/50, I try to push for it but when it is more 60/40 then I tend to listen to Rishabh. As a bowler, you obviously want to take the DRS whevever possible. We've got 2 reviews, so obviously one is for me (laughs off).

Chasing a target at the Ekana Stadium against LSG! Many teams with some of the most skilled and experienced batters have failed this gauntlet as the tracks get sluggish and the bowlers offer them no pace. However, Delhi Capitals today proved that a potent concoction made with the exuberance of youth and the perennially fearless mindset of Rishabh Pant is what is needed to rattle Lucknow on their own turf. A great game for the neutral fan, makes the IPL table a bit more competitive. Let’s see tomorrow if Punjab can pull up any trees and drag down Rajasthan from their perch. Join us then, bye for now!!
